questions.question:
Consider the following ES6 class structure:

```javascript
class BaseEntity {
  constructor(id) {
    this.id = id;
  }
  getInfo() {
    return `ID: ${this.id}`;
  }
}

class User extends BaseEntity {
  constructor(id, username) {
    // Line A
    this.username = username;
  }
  getUserInfo() {
    return `${this.username} - ${this.getInfo()}`;
  }
}

const user = new User(1, 'jsdev');
```

What would happen if `Line A` is the only line missing in the `User` class constructor, and you try to create an instance of `User`? And what is the correct way to fix it?

questions.example:
```javascript
class BaseEntity {
  constructor(id) {
    this.id = id;
  }
}

class User extends BaseEntity {
  constructor(id, username) {
    // Incorrect: try to use 'this' before super()
    // this.username = username; // This line would cause ReferenceError

    // Correct way:
    super(id); // Must call super() first to initialize 'this' from parent
    this.username = username;
  }
}

try {
  const user = new User(1, 'jsdev');
  console.log(user.id); // 1
  console.log(user.username); // jsdev
} catch (e) {
  console.error(e.message);
}
```

```javascript
class Shape {
  draw() {
    return 'Drawing a generic shape.';
  }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
  draw() {
    const parentDraw = super.draw(); // Call parent method
    return `${parentDraw} Specifically, drawing a circle.`;
  }
}

const myCircle = new Circle();
console.log(myCircle.draw()); // Output: Drawing a generic shape. Specifically, drawing a circle.
```

```javascript
class Parent {
  static staticMethod() {
    return 'Parent static method';
  }
}

class Child extends Parent {
  static childStaticMethod() {
    return super.staticMethod() + ' from Child.';
  }
}

console.log(Child.staticMethod()); // Parent static method
console.log(Child.childStaticMethod()); // Parent static method from Child.
```

