```javascript
function outer() {
  let outerVar = 'I am outer';
  function inner() {
    // inner 'closes over' outerVar from outer's lexical environment
    console.log(outerVar);
  }
  return inner;
}
const myFunction = outer();
myFunction(); // Logs: I am outer (even though outer() has finished)
```
Here, `outerVar` is part of `outer`'s lexical environment. `inner` is defined within this environment and 'closes over' it. When `outer()` returns `inner`, `inner` carries a reference to `outer`'s lexical environment, allowing it to access `outerVar` later.

